The main appeal of 3D hydrodynamic simulations is that they can in principle model the interaction between the stellar cores and the envelope gas in a self-consistent way, although scale problems and resolution issues seriously hinder this prospect. Moreover, 3D simulations of the fast inspiral revealed just how non-spherical the CE interaction is, with outflows relatively close to the equatorial plane, and they revealed the complex flow structures involved in Phase (ii) of CE interaction. They also clearly showed that ejecting the envelope using only orbital energy is very difficult, if not impossible, and paved the way to a deeper understanding of the energy exchange, including the impact of recombination energy on the expanding envelope. While—contrary to initial, perhaps naïve, hopes—3D hydrodynamic CE simulations have not provided a convincing value of αCE\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\alpha _\mathrm{CE}$$\end{document} for the energy formalism discussed in Sect. 2.1, they do provide a far deeper understanding of the parameter itself. These and other discoveries, which will be described in detail in Sect. 6.3, have convinced many groups to pursue this investigation avenue. Computers and numerical techniques are, after all, advancing rapidly and enable ever more complex simulations. Yet, this enthusiasm also gives way to the realization that, in the end, it might be a clever combination of techniques that will take the podium.

