As discussed in the previous section, the question of resolving the core of the giant star is not primarily a spatial scale problem; the limiting factor is the timescale problem introduced by the core of the primary star. Depending on its nature, one may hope to resolve the companion. While compact objects such as white dwarfs or neutron stars are too small to achieve sufficient resolution, a main sequence companion may come into reach for future simulations. Still, for a reasonably resolved sun-like companion star, the timescale discrepancy of ∼105\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
