The introduction of a core particle alone, however, does not solve the problem satisfactorily straight away. It introduces two ways of treating stellar material—a particle modeling the core and a grid-based discretization of the envelope. These need to be defined and coupled in a physically consistent way. A naïve approach that simply assigns the mass of the stellar core to the particle leaves a resolution-dependent amount of envelope material in the central grid cell. This high-density material is usually not sufficiently resolved to guarantee a correct treatment of core-envelope interaction. Leaving the envelope profile unaltered, as was common practice in many simulations of dynamical inspiral in CEE, leads to perturbations of the HSE in the envelope structure of the primary star and generates spurious velocities. As a resolution-dependent model, numerical convergence of the results of CE simulations is hard to establish with such a setup.Fig. 11
Radial profiles of density (top left), internal energy (bottom left), pressure (top right), and derivative of pressure (bottom right) of an original mesa model for a 2M⊙\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
