The next grid-based code to be exercised on the CE problem was enzo (Bryan et al. 1995). This code was originally developed for cosmological simulations and Passy et al. (2012) adapted it to the stellar problem. Core and companion were modelled as point masses with the usual softening of the gravitational potentials (see Sect. 4.3.3). Self-gravity was implemented with a fast Fourier transform technique (see Sect. 4.3.2), while the gravity of the two point masses was treated analytically by adding the (softened) potential to that calculated for the gas. Starting out from a 1D stellar model, Passy et al. (2012) mapped a 0.88R⊙\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
